        "## 14.8 Filters, leakage, and forecasting validation\n",
        "\n",
        "Filtering can introduce **look-ahead leakage**. Suppose the goal is to forecast $X_{t+1}$ from information available at time $t$. If we create a centered moving-average feature\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Z_t=\\frac{1}{3}(X_{t-1}+X_t+X_{t+1}),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then $Z_t$ contains the future value $X_{t+1}$. A supervised-learning model trained on $Z_t$ is given information that would not be available at prediction time.\n",
        "\n",
        "For forecasting, causal features are safer:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Z_t=\\frac{1}{m}\\sum_{j=0}^{m-1}X_{t-j}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Even then, validation must respect time order. The filter must be fit or applied inside each training window, and no operation should use future observations when producing training or validation features.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## Practical rule\n",
        "For exploratory plots, centered smoothers are often acceptable. For forecasting features, use causal filters unless you can prove that no future information enters the feature construction.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.9 From Fourier to local time-frequency analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "The Fourier transform represents a series using global sinusoids. This works well when frequency content is stable over time. But many real sequences are **nonstationary in frequency**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- a machine sensor develops a high-frequency vibration only near failure;\n",
        "- an ECG signal has local transient events;\n",
        "- a financial return series has short bursts of volatility;\n",
        "- a traffic series changes its weekly pattern after a disruption;\n",
        "- a speech signal changes frequency content from phoneme to phoneme.\n",
        "\n",
        "A single periodogram tells us which frequencies are present overall, but not when they occur.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Short-time Fourier transform\n",
        "\n",
        "A natural solution is to compute Fourier transforms on local windows. Given a window function $g$, the short-time Fourier transform is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{STFT}_x(u,\\omega)\n",
        "=\\sum_t x_t g(t-u)e^{-2\\pi i\\omega t}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The parameter $u$ localizes time, and $\\omega$ localizes frequency. The squared magnitude\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "|\\operatorname{STFT}_x(u,\\omega)|^2\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a local time-frequency energy measure.\n",
        "\n",
        "The limitation is that the window width is fixed. A narrow window gives good time resolution but poor frequency resolution. A wide window gives good frequency resolution but poor time resolution.\n",
        "\n",
        "Wavelets address this by changing the window width with scale.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.10 Wavelets and multiresolution analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "A **wavelet** is a localized oscillatory function. Unlike a sine wave, which extends forever, a wavelet is concentrated in time.\n",
        "\n",
        "Starting from a mother wavelet $\\psi(t)$, define scaled and translated wavelets by\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\psi_{a,b}(t)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{|a|}}\\psi\\left(\\frac{t-b}{a}\\right),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $a$ is scale and $b$ is location.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Small $a$: compressed wavelet, good for high-frequency local events.\n",
        "- Large $a$: stretched wavelet, good for low-frequency broad behavior.\n",
        "\n",
        "The continuous wavelet transform is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "W_x(a,b)=\\int x(t)\\overline{\\psi_{a,b}(t)}\\,dt.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For discrete data, we often use dyadic scales $a=2^j$ and translations aligned with the sample grid. This leads to the discrete wavelet transform.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Wavelet idea\n",
        "Fourier analysis asks: how much frequency $\\omega$ is present in the whole signal? Wavelet analysis asks: how much scale $a$ is present near time $b$?\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.11 The Haar wavelet\n",
        "\n",
        "The simplest wavelet is the **Haar wavelet**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\psi(t)=\n",
        "\\begin{cases}\n",
        "1, & 0\\leq t<1/2,\\\\\n",
        "-1, & 1/2\\leq t<1,\\\\\n",
        "0, & \\text{otherwise.}\n",
        "\\end{cases}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a pair of observations $(x_0,x_1)$, the Haar transform computes\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "a=\\frac{x_0+x_1}{\\sqrt 2},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        " d=\\frac{x_0-x_1}{\\sqrt 2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The coefficient $a$ is an average, and $d$ is a detail. The inverse transform is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "x_0=\\frac{a+d}{\\sqrt 2},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "x_1=\\frac{a-d}{\\sqrt 2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a longer sequence of length $n=2^J$, the Haar transform repeatedly averages neighboring pairs and stores the differences. This gives a multiresolution representation:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\text{data} = \\text{coarse approximation} + \\text{details at several scales}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The Haar transform is orthonormal, so it preserves energy:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\sum_t x_t^2 = \\sum_k c_k^2,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $c_k$ are the wavelet coefficients.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.12 Python: Haar wavelet transform from scratch\n",
        "\n",
        "The next code block implements a simple orthonormal Haar transform. This avoids hiding the mathematics inside a library."
